Over the past decade,  investors have poured capital into Southeast Asia. Vietnam, in particular,  has benefited. They export a lot of final  assembly of electronics, like some of your iPhones or  your Samsung smartphones. They also export a lot of  apparel. President Trump's tariff  plan could shake up this
trade. Vietnam is highly  vulnerable. Leaders around the world  have asked the White House to back down from the tax  hikes. In response, President Trump  lowered tariff rates to 10% on most countries,  except China. I also have to say 90 day  pauses are not an eradication of tariff risk. The tax hikes on products  across Southeast Asia could
be potent. U.S. imports of Vietnamese  products grew rapidly in recent years. Experts say  this may be connected to foul play from China. Our analysis points to some  tentative evidence of rerouting, particularly by  Chinese firms that newly invested in Vietnam after  2018. If this can be definitively  shown,
countervailing measures  against those particular exporters may be warranted. What could these  developments mean for producers in Vietnam and  their customers in the United States? Factories in Vietnam produce  many consumer goods sold in the U.S. So Vietnam has become a  second largest supplier of
clothing and shoes to the  U.S. after China. So major  American brands source heavily from Vietnam,  for example, Nike. They produce about 50%  of its footwear and 28% of it abroad in Vietnam. Manufacturers in Vietnam,  produce furniture for companies like Wayfair,  and toys for companies like Hasbro and Mattel.
Companies like Apple and  Samsung also rely on Vietnam's manufacturing. You know, Samsung alone  employs 160,000 workers in Vietnam. Between 2018 and today,  more and more companies started actually investing  anew in Vietnam. So Apple coordinated with a  lot of its Taiwanese suppliers to move more  production into Vietnam.
Businesses with supply  chains that run through Vietnam saw their stocks  sink as news of higher import taxes spread. If tariff rates proposed in  April go into effect, they could cost around  $3,800 for the average U.S . household. The U.S . has a much higher level of  gross domestic product per capita when compared to  Vietnam's.
There is simply a lot more  demand in the United States for the kinds of things that  Vietnam exports. Then there is demand in  Vietnam for what the United States exports. And that's a function of the  fact that the two economies are at very, very different  levels of development. So the United States is an  advanced economy.
We tend to export goods that  are capital intensive. Vietnam is a relatively poor  country where demand for things like the new 787,  is going to be much more limited. The White House says that  higher tariff rates will help the U.S. compete with  rising powers like China. In recent years,  businesses have reduced
their production in China  and ramped up in other developing countries,  like Vietnam. This is known as the China  +1 strategy. The way production works  these days, pieces of a product come  from all over the world and then are assembled together. But over the years,  China had become the factory for the world,  and so a lot of supply
chains were entirely located  inside China. So, for example,  an Apple iPhone, all the components would be  produced and then finally assembled in China. But that became risky,  and it became risky as Chinese wages started to go  up, as people had concerns about  too much dependance on a particular country.
And so the insurance  strategy was to open a factory in another country,  say, for example, Vietnam,  or Thailand, or Bangladesh,  or India. One of the reasons that  Vietnam has been on the come up, so to speak,  has been because China has been so successful in its  development model that it is pricing itself out of things  like making t -shirts,
or sewing shoes and that  kind of thing. They've moved on into kind  of higher value added products. China has been accused of  using Vietnam to pass through some exports into  the U.S. This tactic could help China  avoid Trump's 2018 tariffs. You saw a massive increase  happening as a result of those 2018 tariffs.
So, one type of activity was  what what we like to call value added production. So they were importing raw  materials and intermediate products from China into a  country like Vietnam or Thailand, and then doing the  production in Vietnam and exporting. That was the vast  majority of the activity, about 84% of the activity.
But there's a smaller part,  maybe 16%, depending on how you measure  it, which is rerouting,  essentially relabeling products. So saying this is  a product that was originally made in China. No new value added activity  took place in Vietnam and then it was exported as a  Vietnamese product. Economists say the higher  tariff rates under
discussion reflect trade  deficits between the U.S. and other nations. The relationship between the  United States and Vietnam, the trade deficit is  relatively sizable. It has grown in the last  year to be about $123.5 billion. The U.S. under Trump says  that many countries are using unfair trade tactics  like currency manipulation,
to expand their trade  surpluses. One of the things that the  Vietnamese are considering is essentially revaluing  their currency in response to the tariffs,  because if the tariffs are going to raise prices of  Vietnamese producers so much, that a decline in the  currency is maybe the only option, they have to  compensate,
unless they can reach a  settlement with the U.S. government. However, it is already low,  in 2024 already. In April, a delegation from  Vietnam reached out to the White House to strike a  deal. We've already seen  Vietnamese party general secretary contact the U.S. administration, offering to  potentially go down to zero
tariffs on U.S . products  entering Vietnam. The primary driver of this  bilateral trade deficit that the United States has with  Vietnam, is not driven by tariffs or  protectionism on Vietnam's part. It's driven by the  fact that there's just relatively much more demand  in the United States for Vietnamese products than  there is demand in Vietnam
for U.S . products. As tariff rates are  negotiated, countries like Vietnam are  bracing for impact. People have called it like  an unforced error or a self-inflicted wound. But it's worse than that  because it's it's essentially like a suicide  pact that's taking out large other countries along with  the U.S .
economy. The White House did not  respond to CNBC's request to participate in this story. In the year 2000,  the U.S . and Vietnam signed a trade  agreement which took tariff rates down from around 40%  to 3%. Today, exports to the United  States from Vietnam account for 30% of Vietnam's gross  domestic product.
The outlook for the people  of Vietnam who, if we know anything about  history in the last 50 years, have really been  through the wringer. Much of it at the hands of  the United States. The outlook was was very  positive. Once you graduate into that  lower middle income status and your manufacturing  sector is taking off,
this is a period in which  that economic growth is translating into real  household gains, so that the dirt floor  becomes a cement or tile floor. The electricity is on  24 hours a day, as opposed to maybe 8 or 12. That is a really  heartbreaking point in economic development for the  people of Vietnam to be
looking at, potentially  taking a big step back, from their first real taste  of the kind of affluence that we in the West and the  United States in particular, often take for granted.


